<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900427-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>900427-0114.</DOCID><HL>   East Germany Gets   Competition Accord   For Its Drug Firms   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>04/27/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   EUROP</CO><IN>DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)</IN><LP>   FRANKFURT, West Germany -- The East German pharmaceuticalindustry will receive protection from Western competitionuntil the end of 1992, the West German Federation of thePharmaceuticals Industry said.   Under an agreement with the East German pharmaceuticalassociation, German companies will sell drugs only in thecountry for which no comparable East German products areavailable in that period. The supply of basic pharmaceuticalproducts will continue to be provided by East Germancompanies, the two groups agreed.</LP><TEXT>   That will give the East German industry a grace period toadjust itself to Western productivity standards and raise theskill level of its employees ahead of the scheduledcompletion of a single internal market in the EuropeanCommunity at the end of 1992.   Over the next few years, West German drug companies willhelp their East German counterparts to improve theircompetitiveness and fulfill their obligations toward otherEast European countries, the West German federation said.</TEXT></DOC>